title: Test Cubes for Full Color FDM Printing

description.text:
We made these color cubes to test the new XYZ da Vinci Color 3D printer.

The Color Cubes were colored as they were printed, with each extrusion layer "painted" by CMYK ink cartridges inside the printer.

Like most really great ideas, the idea of combining FFF with ink jet color is so elegant and obvious that we can't believe we didn't think of it earlier, but we're glad that XYZ did! The cubes are designed to be impossible to print in color simply by swapping filament at different layer heights; it's fun to hand these cubes to someone familiar with typical desktop 3D printing and watch them try to figure out how they could have been made.

Although adding color to 3D models can sometimes be a challenge, in this case it was very easy. We simply built the model in Tinkercad and assigned colors there before exporting in OBJ format with an MTL texture file. You can play with the Tinkercad file yourself if you want to remix the cube for your own color tests.

Full disclaimer: XYZprinting provided us with a beta version of their da Vinci Color printer for testing, and that's why we designed this model. To tell you the truth, before it arrived we really didn't expect it to work at all, since we had never thought a full-color filament printer would be possible. But we were wrong; the printer really does work, and it really does print in color!

I designed this with a ø7mm mounting hole, it's made for long rods to hold the spools so I only made one mounting hole so you can easily turn the axis up and out of one of the slots so you can add multiple spools. It is usable straight like it is but I used rowokii 's parametric spool holder for this application

description.text:
Original Kickstarter RigidBot R1, has a fixed distance between the bed and the hotend. Any regulation has to be performed moving the position of the ring containing the Z-End Stop switch, or even worse, you may need to touch the 4 bed alignment screws.
That is not very comfortable, especially if you plan to install a glass over the bed, and continue to swap it at any print.

This addon, adds an adjustable end stop knob as found in many RepRap printers.
This is the result of many hours of design, with the goal of building something very efficient, and that could be well integrated with the RigidBot aesthetics.

You will need to completely dismount and remove from his current location the original Z-end stop ring and detach the microswitch board. The microswitch will be installed on this new object at a different location then the original RigidBot. Read the step by step PDF Installing guide in the thingiverse files section.

The object has been designed in a manner to be REALISTIC and that everyone could print, avoiding any strange object that could be printed only using supports, ultra tuned hires printer, fanta-printers...

The parts are already in the correct position to be printed. At the moment are ALL IN ONE, since this give time to small PLA parts to cold while printing the other sections.
All parts are original excluded the knob. The knob is a remix of https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1420598.

I printed them in PLA in an old RepRapPro but you may try also print them in ABS.

REQUIRED PARTS:

  • THE STL printed objects
  • 4 screws M3 x 8mm
  • 2 screws M4 x 16mm
  • 7 nuts M3
  • 9 washers M3
  • 2 screws M3 x 20mm
  • 1 screw M3 x 50mm
  • 1 M3 spring around 20mm (from a pen)
  • 1 brass hexagonal spacer M3 x 10mm

ASSEMBLING:
Follow the installation instruction PDF, and help with the pictures.

title: X-Axis Cable Chain for Replicator 1/CTC Bizer without connector disassembly

description.text:
This is a remix of

Replicator 1 X-Axis Cable Chain by GeraldO, thing:119814

Due to glove size 12 I was not realy motivated to disassemble this micro connector at the end of the X-Axis Stepper Cable.
So I just enlarged GeraldOs thing to 15mm width.
It*s only, that it was not possible to print more than 2 chain elements at a time, due to the wide unsupported bridging distance.
But I rather prefer doing more printjobs, then disassemble micro terminals from a micro connector.
For all steps and print settings you can follow GeraldOs assembly instruction, but you can fully assemble the chain and push through the cable afterwards, ...including the assembled connector ;-)

On my printer it is working very well for 7 month now.

Have fun!

title: 1 inch t-slot extrusion scale up of kossel mini

description.text:
I plan on building several 3d printers, so using locally obtainable large/heavy pieces is a must. Locally all I can find are 1 inch (and larger) T-slot aluminium extrusions. I measured and scaled up by 1.666666667 in replicatorG and printed a small test (partial) piece that seems to fit my extrusions. So I am now printing a full top corner piece (5 stinking hrs) I have 3x600mm and 9x240mm (dude made me convert to inches before he would sell it to me....) in 1 inch, 240mm looks strange. other than the frame I plan to stick to plan sizewise, but I have a feeling that I will have tons of problems, pulley belts attach to this piece, I'm sure I can work around that, but on the bottom piece the step motor mounts probably wont work anymore, and surely other problems. If anyone that can help with this, it would be great...for me.
I'm not going to get bogged down in this design. I am printing a stock kossel mini set and ordering a set of 1515, but my 2nd printer will be this one, and I will make progress as time permits. UPDATE::It looks like I may have it. OpenSCAD is easier than PHP.

comments.text: I am only a beginner with the min kossel but have made 2 frames up and making a few customised components. These are just my quick thoughts that might help if I got it right in my head. If you placed the 25mm frame dead centre over the spot where the 15mm extrusion will go you will instantly throw the other dimension off by 5mm for each side so in effect the glass  / print area would go from 170mm to 160mm but that could be reduced even more you have offset motors and belts etc. If you could extend the outer curve and keep the inside face of the extrusion the same for the 25mm as where the 15mm is then the motors and pulleys etc could all maintain the same locations as the 15mm mini kossel.
comments.author: swinks

comments.text: I didn't just make the hole bigger, I made the whole piece bigger, who knows if that will make it worse or just keep the ratio alltogether. or Maybe I just need slightly longer 240mm peices. Kossel legacy is 600x300

I'm making my own variation for ceramic printing. I'm using 40mm extrusion (that was all I could find in the lengths I wanted at the recycler) It will be 2 feet on the sides and 4 feet high. I'm using Road marker fiberglass rods and neodymium magnets for the connections. Instead of belts, I plan on using spectra line so I don't have to pay for longer belts. Most of the pieces I'm designing from scratch using the Kossel as a reference. However some things like the pulleys and linear bearings (I'm using steel rods as well as extrusions) are already available and I can use printed unmodified. As I get closer to assembly and putting the electronics together I'll put it up on this site for people to laugh at. It really will be an overgrown delta printer.

title: Mode 2 Ghost Parametric Arm Guard TPU/TPE

description.text:
Arm guard for the awesome new Mode 2 Ghost ultralight 5' prop racing frame.
This will:

  • Prevent your motor wires from being cut
  • Hold down wires/esc on your arm
  • not slip when printed in TPU/TPE
  • require 4 cable ties
  • Look clean and smooth
  • hold your antennas like a boss
  • print in plastic (tolerances built in)
  • is parametric (adjust to any frame/esc/thickness/length desired)

Slots for 2.5mm cable ties, print right side up, so that the two sides bridge at top.

Adjustable parametrically, measure your arm width/esc width + tolerance and choose an appropriate wall thickness, length, and height.

Included presets for Mode2 Ghost (4in1 ESC), AstroXSwitch (Aikon SEFM 30A 6s ESCs), and QAV ULX (4in1 ESC).

title: 35mm Film Negative Scanner Attachment for iPhone 6/6s

description.text:
AKA the world's most ridiculous iPhone case! This attaches to your iPhone 6 or 6s and allows you to scan 35mm film negatives.

Autodesk inventor source files are included.

Assembly

Print one of each part. Probably best to print with an opaque filament.

You will also need:

  1. 10 M3 nuts and 10 M3x16 screws (other lengths may work too)
  2. A piece of a suitable diffuser material, and some glue to attach it to the inside of the diffuser box. I used some paper vellum. Cut to fit in the 50x62mm rectangular hole.
  3. A suitable convex or biconvex lens. I used one with a diameter of 25mm and a focal length of 45mm. You can find these cheaply on eBay sold for Google Cardboard.

The lens is necessary because of the relatively long minimum focal distance of the phone's camera. Alternatively the spacer could be lengthened, but this means the negative will take up less of the frame, wasting available resolution. Using a simple (bi)convex lens does introduce some pincushion distortion, but this is easily corrected with GIMP or Photoshop.

Work in progress! To do list:

  • Combine the negative frame and spacer into one part
  • Design an LED light fixture to attach to the diffuser box

This is still a work in progress - we are currently just using this page to share files between students - stay tuned for updates in build instructions - code and lessons to be included!

We are happy to thank 3M and Donorschoose for helping to make this project come to life!

Our Sachem East High School Engineering class created a Robot design to be digitally shared across the globe! Print out an IzzyBot body in your favorite color, gather your robot parts listed in the bill of materials, and follow the instructions to learn how to build and program your own robot. Please share your experience and where you are located in the comments section. We are interested to see how this robot is built and used on every continent!

We chose Infinite Source Sonar Explorer - or "Izzy" for short - for our name because we were researching robotic parts that could be easily sourced in many places along with it being an open source design for educational use.

We were lucky to be funded through DonorsChoose.Org (https://www.donorschoose.org/project/students-design-physical-robots-to-be-sh/2693845) and our donations were matched by 3M. We appreciate all the support for the project and we hope it helps spread open source coding learning resources around the globe!

In small groups, students took individual parts, measured them with dial calipers, and translated their measurements into AutoCAD drawings. Each group worked on a prototype for an area of the body, and when we found a design that would work we started combining the groups until the entire body could be printed. We went through many prototypes and many revisions and after a few weeks were able to print out our ten sets of robot bodies to assemble. We are happy to share the final results with you, please let us know about your success with our robot design!

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Water your Trees and Garden with Ease
The Portable Watering System eliminates the need to drag hoses around your property trying to get that "just right" flow so the roots receive a deep penetrating watering. The system consists of a bucket attached to a hallowed spike. The water from the bucket drips through the spike, penetrating below the surface and directly to the roots. Simply fill the bucket and gravity does the rest.

Control Flow Speeds
The system offers 3 spike choices with different water flows. The #3 spike has an interior diameter of 3 mm and will drain a 5 gallon bucket in 1-2 hours. The #2 spike has a diameter of 2 mm and will drain in 2-4 hours. The #1 spike has a diameter of 1 mm and will drain in 6+ hours or more. The actual drain speed is based upon the type of soil and moisture content. Clay and moist soil will take longer. Loose and dry will be shorter. As they say, your mileage may vary.

Please leave a comment with the drain speeds you are seeing for a five gallon bucket.

Instructions

Print Components
Print a stake of the desired speed and a nut. If you are not sure, I recommend the #2 stake. I find a 40% infill and a .2 mm resolution with 4 or more walls offers the best performance. The stake needs to be strong to penetrate the ground. Optionally you may print a washer and stake cover. The stake cover is used if you leave the stake in the ground and remove the bucket. The cover will prevent debris from clogging the stake. The washer may reduce leaking.

Bucket Prep
Obtain a bucket of the appropriate size. In the US I prefer the Lowes 5 gallon bucket for the unbeatable price of $2.98. Drill a 1" hole in the bottom of the bucket about an inch from the side. Install the spike on the bottom and attach with the optional washer and nut.

Place in the ground, fill and enjoy. When completed you may leave the spike attached to the bucket or leave in the ground. If the latter, print the optional cover to prevent the spike from clogging.

The Certamen quiz team competition from the Junior Classical League involves quiz questions on Greek/Roman subjects. Individual contestants press buzzer buttons when they have an answer. The machine keeps track of the order in which buttons were pressed, subject to the team-lockout rule that once a player on a team presses a button, the other presses from that team don't count. The machine we built was for three teams of four players each. Additionally, so that other school groups could use the machine as a standard quiz machine, there is an option to disregard teams and just keep track of button order.

The school Certamen team needed a machine to practice on, but the official machine is $545 for the standalone system (a variant that plugs into a computer is $435), which was budgetarily infeasible. Plus obviously overpriced!

comments.text: I was thinking about this design and I can only tell that it is very important to make sure the bundle of cables is located and pinned directly in the center. So the neutral axis (the one that doesn't change its length ) is aligned with the chain pivots. Otherwise the cables will be subjected to cyclic stress leading to premature failure.
comments.author: junaling

comments.text: Good point, specially if the bending radius is at it's minimum, those outside the bend will be stretched and those in the inside compressed. it is important to properly arrange the cables and ideally each cable should stay in the same position within the bundle specially in the sections that bend. I find that the bigger diameter cables are not affected that much, but the smaller ones are. I've added several sized braces to help in arranging the cables and also so the cables stay within 3mm of the center, this would also give the cables some movement and not completely pinned to the chain just like a normal closed channel chain would.

description.text: Was looking for some lower cost plastic for my Replicator MakerBot. Turns Octave sells a bunch of colors on Amazon for reasonable prices. Unfortunately, after purchasing, I realized that the spool is of a different design than what you get from MakerBot. The spool is not only thicker, but has a much smaller hole. So what better solution than to make my own holder. So I cranked out a quick design based on the original MakerBot holder design, but one that fit the hole of the Octave spool.

This is still a version one design. It may appear large, but the stl should be accurate to the size needed, as noted in the description the Octave spools are much wider. I have it print so that it is stronger in the vertical direction that supports all the weight. I also printed it with about 50% fill, again to make it as strong as possible. Because it was so long, I had a bit of warping when it was done, which required that I needed to do some extra sanding to make the spool fit loosely enough to ensure it would spin without getting caught. I used a dremel tool to help speed up the sanding process. If you can do everything you can to avoid the warping when printing it, that should help in reducing the amount of sanding needed. Other than that, it should print fine. Ideas for V2
  • Would like to provide it with a bit more tolerance to avoid needed to sand anything afterwards.
  • I've also noticed that the spool isn't held far enough away from the back of the MakerBot as to avoid potential rubbing. Need to adjust the design for that.

This is a fairly simple manual 5-stage encryption tube. This device can scramble a short message that can only be decoded with the proper passcodes. It also has an optional custom cylinder for those who don't want to use the default model.

By entering 2 passwords, vertically rearranging the numbered cylinders and turning the central protruding ring on each cylinder, the user can trace from top to bottom, or vice-versa, to transmute each character by matching the characters on the edges of each cylinder.

This design is partly modeled off the simple but surprisingly effective Enigma machine used during WWII until the German naval machine was cracked by Alan Turing. This version, however, is purely a mechanical rather than an electro-mechanical cypher, so it smaller but slower, and could even potentially be shrunk to fit in one's pocket.

This model was generated by painstakingly reverse engineering the Iris Diaphragm for Steampunk Goggles project by IrisCalculator. Solidworks files are provided so you can make tweaks where neccessary (e.g. you can make the pins longer to prevent the blades from falling out).

All original measurements are maintained.

MOTION SIMULATION QUIRK
Note the mates in the assembly are not fully defined. This was intentional, in order to achieve the "slanted pivoting" orientation of the blades. Further work to fully define the mates would result in a more robust assembly, but may not be easy (unless you want to just make all of the blades parallel to each other). Stringing Clean-up

Printing small structures with lots of retraction inducing lattices (assuming PLA) means possibly printing hotter, slower, w/o retration, or some combination. You'll often be left with some or a lot of stringing. The best way to clean it up is to use a Butane Torch, ignite the torch, and very quickly run it over the surface.

I prefer a method similar to airbrushing in which you start off the part, move across it in one pass, and off the part. Simply: Turn on torch, move on, across, move off, turn off torch.

Hope that helps.
